Incredible photos of #KingsCross by @griffie.visuals! üî•üì∏‚ù§Ô∏è The Western Concourse is the largest single-span structure in Europe, and was actually inspired by Victoria glasshouses like Kew Gardens, and designed to give passengers an uplifting experience before embarking on their journey. @MrLondon on #ShadThames... definitely one of my favourite streets in London... in the late 1800‚Äôs these bridges connected the old riverside buildings to the storehouses and mills, so clippers (small cargo ships) could unload their cargo such as spices, dried fruit, teas, coffee etc - this area was quite literally known as the ‚Äòlarder of London‚Äô. Over time to city moved to containers which were unloaded further east, so by the 1970‚Äôs this whole area transitioned to residential and now feature expensive apartments, cafes, bars and restaurants. But it‚Äôs still a treat to walk under these bridges and soak the history up! And it‚Äôs right next to Tower Bridge. @MrLondon on Southwark Street - the Grade II Listed building on the left is known as the ‚ÄúHop Exchange‚Äù - Hops are obviously used in the brewing industry and they would be harvested from farms & "hop gardens" in places like Kent in the 19th century and then brought by railway to #LondonBridge Station, or by boat up the River #Thames. I just want people to be aware and safe. People just need to be wise to the fact there are organised gangs on mopeds and bikes, and they know that we‚Äôre all stopping to gawp at the Christmas lights, so they come from behind on their bikes and snatch your phone and BOOM... they‚Äôre gone. üò≠ We all rely on our phones so much, so it‚Äôs worth being safe on the streets, and also taking time to check that your photos and docs are all backed up, because if you lose your memories it‚Äôs a pretty painful experience. So use things like iCloud or backup to your PC etc. üëåüèº Also think about your two-factor authentication for Instagram and have it set up to a different number than the one being stolen (theoretically)... or you will get locked out like I did. üôàü§¶üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è I have a spare PayAsYouGo phone / SIM for this purpose now so I can get back online quicker and faster. Oh and if it happens, which I hope it won‚Äôt, call your network provider - ask a police officer if needs be - to block the SIM to the phone. üì∏ AND for photography, whether with a camera or phone, have a friend watch over you whilst you‚Äôre taking pics. I‚Äôve got so many messages from people who‚Äôve had the same thing happen. So many phones. And a few with expensive cameras. So we all need to be alert. I was the 9th person in 1 HOUR to get caught in the same spot opposite Selfridges. BE AWARE. #VEDAY75 | Victory in Europe Day, generally known as VE Day or V-E Day, is a day celebrating the formal acceptance by the Allies of World War II of Nazi Germany's unconditional surrender of its armed forces on Tuesday, 8 May 1945, marking the end of World War II in Europe. @MrLondon checking in. I‚Äôm contemplating #ArmisticeDay as our day of remembrance draws to a close, marking 100 years since the end of World War One. My heart is full of gratitude for those that fought for the freedom I have today, especially my forefathers. Pic 1 is my Great Grandad who fought in WW1. He was blown up in France and suffered serious shrapnel wounds. An angelic soldier and comrade pulled him off the battlefield, and after being repatriated to England, he survived his injuries and went onto marry and have 4 children. He‚Äôd enlisted underage at 17. Pic number 2 is my Grandad who was taken as a prisoner of war when Singapore fell in 1942. He was caught up in the Thai/Burma railway construction known as the Death Railway, designed to take Japanese Imperial Army troops and supplies from Bangkok to Burma. One man died for every railway sleeper laid. üòî The 3rd pic is me. 4 generations on. Walking in #RegentsPark without any fear. Today I can write this whilst eating a roast dinner surrounded by friends. Whatever may trouble me now seems to pale into insignificance. Tonight I will be watching ‚ÄúThe Railway Man‚Äù - it‚Äôs all about the aforementioned PoW railway and stars Colin Firth & Nicole Kidman. It‚Äôs my way of reflecting upon my family‚Äôs own sacrifices, at a time when the entire nation reflects on many conflicts, many lives lost, many sacrifices made. My heart is full of gratitude and my prayers are that those in modern day conflict would know peace. Lots of love to everyone. #LestWeForget üá¨üáß‚ù§Ô∏èüá¨üáß // #thisislondon #london #rememberanceday #ww1 #ww2

A slice of history... #GuyFawkes night or ‚ÄúBonfire Night‚Äù is when Brits gather under firework lit skies to watch dummies burn on bonfires! üî• Why?! ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è It‚Äôs actually the anniversary of an attempt to blow up the #HousesOfParliament - known as the Gunpowder Plot. The dummies - or Guy - refer to Guy Fawkes who was part of the plot. Back in 1605 the plan was to blow up King James I and his government! England was Protestant. The plotters were Catholic. 36 barrels of explosive gunpowder were hidden in the cellars of parliament, but the king‚Äôs supporters got hold of a letter warning a friend to stay away from the Houses of Parliament on the 5th November. The plotters were tumbled and subsequently executed. The plot was immortalised in a nursery rhyme ‚ÄúRemember, remember, the fifth of November, gunpowder, treason and plot...‚Äù // Have a wonderful evening everyone! üì∏ @tmnikonian üî• // #thisislondon #london #bonfirenight #fireworks üá¨üáß‚ù§Ô∏èüá¨üáß

Solidarity is a big part of #LondonFromHome:‚Å£"I'm used to walking across the metropolis along linear roads, crossing zones to communicate with those who share my life. Meandering my way through the crowds of tourists taking pictures of Big Ben and Westminster Abbey and I occasionally get bellowed 'excuse me, can you take a picture of me?‚Äô And of course I can spare a few seconds on their request. But now the feeling of walking around London in near silence is still a very strange feeling. ‚†Ä‚Å£‚†Ä‚Å£Living in an apartment complex, you never really get attached to people as we all hold our guard up. Yet now being unable to travel freely most of us have turned to our neighbours, hurriedly discarding the unspoken agreement to disregard each other. I found a note slipped under the door a day before the lockdown: "Dear neighbour, if you have fallen ill and/or need any help with shopping, cooking or having medicine during self-isolation, please send us a call." I told my friends, and as the days went by, several of them mentioned receiving similar messages. People at my floor were unexpectedly able to hand their mobile number out to total strangers. It provoked an unexpected thrill; a sense of neighbourly culture, a way outside our immediate circle to show compassion.‚†Ä‚Å£‚†Ä‚Å£As haven't seen my parents or my sisters family for 2 months video calling helps a lot and boosts my morale when thoughts get rough. For now, I have my neighbours who are my family during this tough time." üì∏xüìù by @krixhhna

The news has been difficult to watch for many months now but more so over the last few days. As a medic that's currently on maternity leave, I feel like I'm watching from the sidelines as my colleagues battle on. And from first-hand stories from friends on the frontline, I can tell that staff are at breaking point.-Today there are more people in hospital with COVID in England than EVER BEFORE. Speaking up about this isn't trying to stir panic, it's trying to raise awareness about what things are like. And I get that "pandemic-fatigue" is real and people are tired, but so are NHS staff. More and more people are dying and hospitals are struggling. So please remember to continue to take things seriously and continue following the rules.-Today's shot comes from @banubilecen and is also a reminder that there's a full moon tonight, the final one of 2020, called the Cold Moon. Another empty London, this time of the gorgeous Tower Bridge which probably hasn't opened to any large boats in months! üòØ Thanks @andresbalcazar_ for this stunner! üì∏-Today I wanted to talk about something I've been thinking about a lot: mental health and how important it is to be kind to each other. Especially when we're going through a period in our lives like this, which has never happened to any of us before. Everyone's fighting their own battles and we need to remember that it might not be obvious. Think before you speak and consider, is what I'm about to say true, helpful, necessary and above all, kind? I read somewhere today: be sure to taste your words before you spit them out, which is so powerful. ‚ù§Ô∏è-At a time like this, it's ok not to be super productive. It's ok if you're not learning a new skill or developing in another way. It's even ok if you feel like you're not being the sort of friend that you normally want to be. I come home on some days after work and crash for the evening by 8pm! We're all dealing with different things and taking it a day at a time. If you're feeling like things are getting too much - please remember that there is so much support out there. As a doctor currently in GP, I speak to people about their mental health on a daily basis, and it's been a lot worse over the last few months due to covid-19. So please carry on talking to people around you about how you're feeling, share with others, and speak to your GP too if you need to! Just a few thoughts there for hump day! ‚ù§Ô∏è-#prettycitylondon #thisislondon #toplondonphoto #prettylittlelondon #cntraveler #travelerinlondon #iamatraveler #mytinyatlas #ww #myoklstyle #visitlondon #visitbritain #visitengland #lovegreatbritain #mydarlinglondon #forbestravelguide #passionpassport #thatsdarling #bbcbritain #living_europe #timeoutlondon #culturetrip_ldn #hello_worldpics #guardiantravelsnaps #beautifuldestinations #suitcasetravels #bbctravel #topeuropephoto-

Let's talk about wearing masks and gloves in public. üß§üò∑-I've lost count of the number of people I see on a daily basis on my drive to and from work being out and about wearing masks and gloves. I get it - they make people feel safe. But are we using these in the right way? I've seen people wearing masks and gloves when driving on their own. I've seen people wearing gloves and holding their phones to their ears, chatting away. I've seen someone pull off a glove that he was wearing, with his teeth because his other hand was full. There is a lot of misinformation out there. Here's some things I've wanted to clarify:-üëÄ Most of the masks out there don't cover your eyes so there's no protection from getting the virus that way.-üß§ Wearing gloves protects your hands but then touching other things (phone, wallet, keys, your face, etc) with those gloves just transfers germs onto these things! You might as well not wear gloves in the first place. It also makes you less likely to wash your hands as often!-üò∑ Most masks aren't made to act as a filter for the virus. There are gaps around the sides so you can easily be sucking in air from these gaps. Just blow out when wearing a mask, and see where you feel the air on your face - those are all gaps! Some people argue that it's still more protection than nothing but it's worrying if people use these as a false reassurance.-‚ùå Taking masks and gloves off. Limit the contact you make with the outside of the mask or gloves. There's a potential that the outside is covered with germs. Discard appropriately into a bin and wash your hands afterwards!-A lot of this may seem like common knowledge but you'll be surprised at what I saw on the way home from work today. So I wanted to put it into writing. Please share with friends, to stories, etc and tag others too!-Thanks for the fab shot as always by @sarashakeel üì∏-

The conversations with families of patients suffering from covid-19 are the hardest. I had a patient this week who had to be isolated in the hospital, like many others, and so his family couldn't visit him. He was deteriorating. His son called the phone in A&E and I picked up. He asked if I could let his dad know that they loved him. That his mum was waiting for her husband at home, and that she had left his dinner out on the table for him, so hurry up and come home so it doesn't go cold.-I just about kept it together. üíî Sending out my love to all those families with loved ones in hospital right now, stay strong.-#doctor #storiesfromthefrontline #frontline #nhs #nhsdoctor ##allwhatsbeautiful #underthefloralspell #englishgarden #gardeninspiration #urbangreen #flowerstagram #flowersofinstagram #flower_daily #gardening #gardendesign #colorcolourlovers #flowersmakemehappy #springinlondon #visitlondon #thisislondon #london #covid19 #covid

How's it going, London? üëã-For those of you that follow along on my stories, you may know that I split my work life over paediatrics for half the week and GP for the other half. It's a unique position to be in over this covid-19 crisis, because I'm working in the hospital and in the community.-I've been in paediatric A&E over the last few weeks and I've noticed a massive drop in the number of kids coming in. Maybe parents are managing minor illnesses on their own, which is great. But I've also seen a rise in the number of children coming in late - and therefore they are more unwell when they get to us and they're having to go to paediatric ICU for simple conditions that we could have managed easily if they'd come to us earlier. It seems that parents are terrified of coming to the hospital due to coronavirus but please remember, the paediatric A&E departments are open and safe for you to come to if you need it. Please come earlier rather than later if you are worried and if your child has symptoms of ANY illness.-Please share this message as far as you can because it will help get the message out. We've never seen this department this quiet before and it's worrying! Thank you as always ‚ù§Ô∏è-#doctor #doctorlife #paediatrics #emergency #emergencydepartment #nhs #nhsworker #nhsdoctor #corona #covid19 #coronavirus #coronalondon #LondonCity #london #londonlive #londonlife #londoner #thisislondon #london_only #londontown #igerslondon #london4all #uk

Telephone consultations in the crisis üìû‚ö†-Most of the GP practices in my local area have switched to telephone consultations. For some, more experienced GPs, that transition has been smoother than for others. I'm still training and I've not had much practice with diagnosing a patient without seeing them or examining them. But due to the coronavirus crisis, we've been left with no choice, thrown into the deep end, all to avoid patients coming in and spreading this virus to the most vulnerable.-Which brings me onto what I had to do today. I generated a list of every patient, over the age of 90, registered to our practice. These are amongst some of the most vulnerable people in our population. I was given the task of calling them and discussing end of life care decisions, in light of the risks they are facing from this virus. Can you imagine how difficult conversations like that are, over the phone, without being able to see the patient's reaction or hold their hand? Can you imagine how scary it would be to talk about dying, especially at a time like this? It was difficult. I talked to each patient about the virus and asked if they had any questions initially. I checked that they were all staying inside and limiting contact from the outside world. I checked if they had thought about what they wanted to happen to them, if they were to become unwell. I asked if they had thought about where they would like to be treated, if they would like to go into hospital or not, and if things got so bad, would they want to be resuscitated, knowing that the chances of survival would be tiny. After working through the list of patients, one after the other, answering their questions and their family's worries, I stopped. I realised I was shattered, and emotionally drained. None of this is what we've planned for, but it's the reality. And the patients were grateful to have these discussions in advance, to ensure their wishes were respected, which is ultimately what's most important ‚ù§Ô∏è-Hoping that sharing my experiences during this pandemic is insightful and again, please stay home to protect our most vulnerable. ‚ù§Ô∏è-#doctor #nhs #gp #juniordoctor #covid19 #coronavirus

Coronavirus and mental health üß†-I've been getting a lot of questions on the impact of social distancing on mental health. It is difficult, facing the prospect of staying at home and avoiding other people and I know a lot of people will feel anxious about the virus in general, but there are things that you can do to help.-TAKE CARE OF YOUR MENTAL HEALTH:1. Don't keep re-reading the same advice if it's making you feel anxious. Let others know you are struggling. Breathing exercises can help you feel more in control.2. If you're anxious about washing your hands, set a limit for 20 seconds and then stop. Plan to do something after you have washed your hands, to distract yourself.3. Keep in touch! Video chat, phone calls, text. Make plans to watch a show/read a book separately and then you can discuss this when you speak next!4. Listen to a chatty radio station or a podcast if your home feels too quiet.5. Plan how you're going to spend your time if this is something you would find helpful.6. Eat well, try to keep active with at-home workouts (including cleaning your house, dancing to music, going up and down the stairs), and stay hydrated.7. Go out into your garden if you can, spend time with the windows open, look out at the sky/birds/other animals. Let as much natural light in as you can.8. Keep your mind occupied - books, magazines, films, podcasts, puzzles... There are also ebooks and audiobooks available!-Hope this is helpful, I'll share other useful resources on my stories as always! Please share this with anyone you think might find it helpful and feel free to share it to your stories too! We checked out Carnaby Street which is looking incredible with their new Project Zero, ocean-themed Christmas lights this year!-Prepare to be immersed into a theatrical underwater scene, there's a floating kelp forest, bright, pink coral and the deep, blue sea! It's all made sustainably, using repurposed fishing netting, over 500m of post-use bubbled wrap and over 1,500 recycled plastic bottles! Over 100L of water-based, eco-friendly, vegan paint has been used for this world-first installation too! And the power used for the lights is 100% renewably sourced too!-The message is simple: One Ocean One Planet, highlighting the urgent need to protect and restore the ocean and the damaging effects of climate change! Tag everyone who would love to see this!-

#ad | We're always going on about the nutritional value of our food but what we learnt this bank holiday weekend is that many of the nutrients break down with exposure to indoor lights like those at the supermarket and in your own home. The @lightdamageisreal campaign showed us that light goes through the translucent packaging that milk comes in, breaking down nutrients like vitamins A, B2 and D3 üò± We couldn't believe that this also changes the appearance, freshness and taste of milk!-The #lightdamageisreal pop up in Notting Hill gives you a chance to shop in the dark with night goggles (which is how you'd have to shop if you wanted to keep your food protected from the light) and you'll be able to learn about Noluma that certifies light-protected packaging so that you know you've got the highest level of protection for your products! Check them out until Thursday and find out more by clicking the link in our bio!-

#ad | Talking about mental health is something that's really important. Being a doctor and working in an inner-London GP surgery, I've seen a huge range of mental health problems firsthand, from depression to anxiety to post-traumatic stress disorder. And it's not just the mental burden, there are real physical effects on a person's appetite, weight, sleep and overall day to day life. It's something that's not openly spoken about and a lot of my patients find it difficult to open up about it. Personally, I find the most relief from talking to my husband when I'm feeling particularly down or stressed and I encourage him to do the same, especially as men are a lot more likely to keep their emotions to themselves. But sometimes you may feel that you can't talk to family or friends and that's also ok - there are still other places and people that can help.-That's why we've partnered with #CroydonTalkingTherapies which is a free and confidential mental health service for adults, if you live in London and are registered with a Croydon GP. They can provide support for a wide variety of mental health problems and offer therapies that range from online sessions and group sessions, to one to one therapy sessions with counsellors. It's so important to raise awareness about these #NHS services that are available when you need extra help and I'm so proud to use my platform to do so. Search for Croydon Talking Therapies to find out more or click the link in our bio! https://bit.ly/2FoUSS6-And if this is something you think you'd benefit from but don't live in Croydon, do speak to your GP about how you're feeling and they can point you to the local services available to you!-Let's talk more openly about mental well-being and help reduce the stigma! @nhsenglandldn‚ù§Ô∏è

üá≤üá¶ H E A R T üá≤üá¶Our last Morocco post is dedicated to our driver and tour guide Hamid @corazondemarruecos ‚ô•Ô∏è Corazon de Marruecos means Heart of Morocco in Spanish and we definitely felt that we experienced that on this trip. Hamid was born and raised in the Sahara desert and has been doing these tour guides since he was 20 years old, showing his country to people from all over the world. He has learnt different languages simply by being around tourists. He was so kind and patient with us this entire trip, waiting for us to get the right pictures and taking us to the best places that weren't even on our list, as well as making sure we got to see everything we set out to. And our car was absolutely fabulous, such a luxury to be driven around in a 4 x 4 across Morocco's varied landscapes from deserts to mountains!-If you guys ever want to do a trip like ours, where we visited 7 cities/towns in 8 days, the only way to do it is by driving. Some people drive on their own but seeing the tiny roads inside the cities and the bends along the cliffsides in the mountains, we're so glad we left it to the professionals. Hamid drove for 10 hours on our longest day and still had a smile on his face at the end of it üôà He was also always on time which made our life so much easier!-When we left, we felt like we were a little family and it definitely feels like we've left a part of our hearts in Morocco. We hope that you've all enjoyed our journey as much as we have enjoyed sharing it, and hope it inspires some of you to visit this beautiful country one day. I'm in the process of writing out a detailed blog of our entire itinerary for those of you that have asked, so I'll share that once it's finished ‚ô•Ô∏è-|| Discounted excursion ||

üá≤üá¶ B A H I A A N D B Y E üá≤üá¶We went and visited the famous Bahia palace just before we said goodbye to Morocco and our incredible riad @riadtibibt üïäÔ∏è-The Bahia Palace, meaning brilliance in Arabic, is one of the best-preserved historical sites in Marrakech. Built between 1866 and 1867 by Si Moussa, this sprawling palace is set over two acres and features 150 rooms! Each of the rooms are decorated in truly elegant Moroccan style with carved stucco and cedarwood, impressive zellig fireplaces as well as a large and small riad surrounded by citrus trees!-It was a wonderful way to end our Moroccan trip of a lifetime and we said goodbye to our stunning riad with one final serving of Moroccan tea (we had several cups every single day and can't tell you how much we'll miss this!)-Tag everyone who would love to go here!-

üá≤üá¶ M A J O R E L L E üá≤üá¶The Jardin Majorelle in Marrakech is one of the most visited sites in Morocco so we had to pay a visit on our last day. It took French painter Jacques Majorelle forty years of passion and dedication to create this enchanting, botanical garden which is two and a half acres big!-We loved the buildings here and their Moorish charm, with a hint of Art Deco, and they were painted in amazingly vibrant primary colours üíôüíõ The villa houses the Islamic Art Museum of Marrakech, the Berber Museum and famously the Musee Yves Saint Laurent!-Travelling with @corazondemarruecos üöô Tag everyone who would love this!-

üá≤üá¶ M A R R A K E C H üá≤üá¶Our last night. We can't quite explain how incredible this trip has been and how amazing it's been interacting with you all and sharing our journey! We left Casablanca after visiting the mosque and drove down to Marrakech, where this epic road trip began 8 days previously.-Our riad was another stunner: @riadtibibt which means the house of birds and it was incredible, with the most eclectic collection of decor and something new to find around every corner. We hadn't stayed in anywhere like this and we loved exploring the different floors, the range of books and other bits and bobs! Our room was the largest one in the riad, the house within the house, and again, it was decorated outrageously fabulously üòÇüëå-We had a few more places to see in Marrakech before we flew home, post to come! Tag everyone who would love this!-|| Complimentary Stay ||-

üá≤üá¶ H A S A N I I üá≤üá¶A post dedicated to the beauty of the largest mosque in Africa üôè There is no way to describe this place except to call it grand and we were blown away by the intricacy and elegance of the decor inside.-We had a guided English tour and walked on beautiful red carpets barefoot and then made our way down to where worshippers cleanse themselves before prayer. Such a beautiful place!-Tag everyone who would love to see this!-

üá≤üá¶ C A S A B L A N C A üá≤üá¶Yesterday our Instagram broke and wouldn't let me upload anything (did the same thing happen to any of you guys?!)-Anyways, if you've been following our trip on a map, you may realise that our roadtrip of Morocco is coming to an end as we head back down to Marrakech to complete a full circle! We headed from Chefchaoeun with our driver @corazondemarruecos to the capital city Rabat and then arrived late evening to the city of Casablanca, which is home to the largest mosque in Africa, Hasan II. We couldn't believe our luck when we realised our hotel room looked straight out onto it!-We had been told to check out the night life in Casablanca, so we headed to the Sky 28 bar and captured this insane view! As we made our way back to the hotel (at 2am!) I found a deserted road with a row of palm trees and had to get a picture (despite almost falling asleep) and then just before we got to our hotel, we saw the mosque again, against the night sky, and managed to capture a picture with the stars! üåüüôè (SWIPE üëâ)-We were so excited to go and see the inside of the mosque the following morning - pictures to come! Tag everyone who would love to see these!-

üá≤üá¶ D J E L L A B A üá≤üá¶The djellaba is a loose-fitting unisex outer robe which originates from Morocco. The word literally means attractive. They are traditionally made of wool in different shapes and colours and have the characteristic pointed hood which is supposed to match the traditional babouche pointed slippers. It also protects the wearer from the sun and sand storms as well as act as a pocket to fit bread or groceries!-We had to get ourselves the traditional wool djellabas which were handmade by the women in the surrounding mountains and got the Chefchaoeun colour! We then stumbled across some peacocks and had an impromptu photoshoot (swipe) and also found the most incredible scent shop with solid perfumes that make Lush look like an imposter üòÇ-Finally as we were leaving Chefchaoeun and our wonderful hosts @casameryemchefchaouen, some of the market sellers asked for a picture as they saw me snapping away. They came up with their own pose and swipe to the last picture to see the final result! üòÇ I love Moroccan people! üá≤üá¶-Tag everyone who would love this!-

üá≤üá¶ C H E F C H A O U E N üá≤üá¶From Fes we headed to the blue pearl of Morocco, Chefchaoeun, which is in the northwest of Morocco in the Rif mountains. This place is a striking because of it's incredible blue-washed buildings which is said to symbolise the sky and the heaven üíô We stayed in @casameryemchefchaouen which was a very traditional apartment in the heart of the old Medina, right in the middle so we were able to explore upwards and hike up the mountain for incredible views as well as explore down into the main square. I couldn't quite believe it was all real, and kept feeling like I was in some sort of film set!-This was one of our highlights of our entire trip, and you guys NEED to go here when you head to Morocco! Tag everyone who would love this! Happy (not-so) blue Monday! üíôüòÇ-|| Discounted Stay ||-

üá≤üá¶ T A N N E R Y üá≤üá¶One of the main things to see in Fes is the leather tannery which is over 1000 years old. Initially I was completely put off the idea, reading reviews online but we had some spare time before we left Fes so we braved going to find it. To get the best view you have to enter one of the many leather stores that surround the tannery as they have large viewing terraces. These shops are stacked floor to ceiling with every colour of leather goods (swipe to see! üëâ)-We followed the signs on the walls (not the directions of people trying to get you lost!) and approached an alleyway of leather shops. The shop we entered had the number 14 written at the top of the doorway. The shopkeeper called us in and we made it very clear we didn't want to buy anything. He said this was fine and we could pay whatever tip we wanted to at the end. So we followed him in and we were given mint to smell to protect us from the stench.-It didn't smell as bad as I had read and it was fascinating to see these rows of over-sized painters‚Äô palettes all glistening under the Moroccan sun. The animal skins are first put in the white pots which contain a mixture of water, limestone, and pigeon droppings(!) After 2-3 days, the skins are washed and transferred to the brown pots to be coloured using cedar wood (brown), poppy flower (red), indigo (blue), henna (orange), mint (green), and saffron (yellow).-Seeing the hides and skins was confronting, especially for someone who's trying to be as vegan as possible when it comes to my food choices. It's safe to say I will never buy another leather product again but it was important to see this medieval process still being used.-Tag everyone who would be interested in this and save to your collections to keep these tips for your trip!-

üá≤üá¶ R A I N B O W S üá≤üá¶The souks of Fes were amazing and we wish we could have explored them more, there are so many endless alleyways and turns and we were so lucky to stumble across this beautiful rainbow street!-It's notoriously hard to find so we're going to try our best to explain where it is: Go to the blue gate Bab Boujloud, take the first left, then the first right and you'll be on Rue Talaa Kebira. Walk down and keep an eye on the right, and you'll see it (the colour gets better as you walk down by the way)! It connects Rue Talaa Kebira to Rue Talaa Sghira üòç Hope that helps, save this photo to your collection to keep these instructions for later!-We absolutely loved this street and couldn't quite believe our eyes! üåà Tag everyone who would love to see this too!-

üá≤üá¶ F E S üá≤üá¶After the longest drive of our Moroccan road trip, we arrived in the city of Fes. After the serenity of the Sahara, Fes was a chaotic explosion of colour, sounds and smells, a warren of tiny alleyways that we were warned we would never find our way out of if we got lost. Slightly exhausted, we arrived at our riad @palaisamani and if you caught my stories, you would have seen how utterly blown away I was.-The little alleyways you walk down to get here are dark and narrow, and suddenly as you enter this riad, you walk onto an open courtyard with stunning trees, birds singing and grand pillars. From the outside, you have no idea that this is what is on the other side. This riad is located within the walls of the ancient Medina, but you completely forget about that once you're inside. The rooms are incredible, the staff were all so attentive, the dinner was had at their restaurant, Eden at Palais Amani, was outstanding and you can really tell that this once used to be a palace.-Swipe to see me dancing around in the grand corridors on the beautiful tiles, pretending to be a princess in her palace üòÇ What an absolute dream ‚ô•Ô∏è-Tag everyone who would love to these these pictures!-|| Complimentary Stay ||-

üá≤üá¶ G A M E OF T H R O N E S üá≤üá¶-Ait-Ben-Haddou is one of Morocco‚Äôs World Heritage Sites and it was also used as a set for Game of Thrones! But its famous for much more than being a backdrop, in the 17th century it became one of the most important ksars in the region. The outside walls of mud and clay protect the town which is built onto the side of a hill. The buildings are packed tight with narrow pathways that wind around each other and unexpectedly turn into steep staircases. At the very top is a fortress as a last line of defence.-So interesting to walk around this piece of history, listening to traditional music (see our highlighted stories for a video!) and seeing the narrow pathways lined in colour! Tag everyone who would love to see these pictures!-Travelling with @corazondemarruecos üöô-

üá≤üá¶ A R G A N O I L üá≤üá¶-After leaving Marrakech, we made our way through the Atlas mountains. We saw some incredible, panoramic views as we rode down the winding roads with our tour guide @corazondemarruecos who stopped us at the best view points (swipe to the end to see!) He then took us to a roadside shop where he told us we'd see pure Moroccan argan oil being made üòç We saw ladies cold pressing the argan seed to produce the oil which apparently retains the oil‚Äôs high Vitamin E properties and it was absolutely fascinating to see, expectedly expensive to buy, but I had to get a bottle! üôà-Tag everyone who would love to see these!-

‚ùå J A R D I N S E C R E T ‚ùå-This elegant 19th-century palace and the traditional Islamic gardens were so beautiful and we found such peace here after the chaos of the souks. This is one of the largest and most ancient palaces of the medina of Marrakech. The museum provides a wealth of historical information about Marrakech's architecture and gardens and the cafes offer fresh, homemade products üëå-A must for your Marrakech list, tag everyone who would love to see this!-

‚ùå S O U K S ‚ùå-The souks of Marrakech are the largest in Morocco and famed throughout the world as some of the most exotic marketplaces to shop in. We'd heard a lot about them before going (mainly from you guys) and we didn't really know what to expect but I can tell you now that this was one of my most favourite experiences so far. A complete maze of shadowy alleys and passages, we got completely lost in a world of multicoloured carpets, silk kaftans, spices, antiques, lanterns, pottery and jewellery. A complete sensory overload and we loved every minute of the hours we spent here.-Tag everyone who would love to see these pictures!-

Time for something a little bit personal, but seeing as you guys message us all the time about our husband vs wife stories, we thought we'd share a picture from the big day itself. Last weekend we stayed in one of @staymerino's incredible apartments and it was such a lovely weekend stay in our city. We'd definitely recommend considering them for your accommodation for your trip to London, whether that's with the family, on a business trip or a romantic getaway, they have apartments of all shapes and sizes!-What we were blown away by was the attention to detail, each apartment is themed and has so many touches to make your stay feel like home, unlike the standard hotel.
